        <h2>What is the SBIR/STTR Program?</h2>
        <p>The Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) and Small Business Technology Transfer (STTR) programs represent the largest source of federal funding for innovative small businesses in the United States. With an annual budget of approximately $4.3 billion, these programs encourage small businesses to engage in federal research and development with significant potential for commercialization.</p>

        <h3>Eligibility Requirements</h3>
        <p>To qualify for SBIR/STTR funding, your business must meet specific criteria:</p>

        <h4>Business Structure & Location</h4>
        <ul>
        <li>Must be a for-profit business located in the United States</li>
        <li>Meet small business definition (generally 500 or fewer employees, including affiliates)</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Ownership Requirements</h4>
        <ul>
        <li>At least 51% owned and controlled by U.S. citizens, permanent residents, or qualifying small businesses</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Principal Investigator</h4>
        <ul>
        <li><strong>SBIR</strong>: Principal Investigator must be primarily employed (at least 50%) by the small business</li>
        <li><strong>STTR</strong>: Principal Investigator can be employed by either the small business or collaborating research institution</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Research Focus</h4>
        <ul>
        <li>Projects must address agency-specific R&D topics and priorities</li>
        <li>Must demonstrate potential for commercialization</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Participating Federal Agencies</h3>
        <p>Eleven federal agencies participate in the SBIR/STTR programs:</p>
        <ul id="agencies-list">
        <li><strong>Department of Defense (DOD)</strong> - Largest funding source</li>
        <li><strong>Department of Health and Human Services (HHS)</strong> - NIH, CDC, FDA</li>
        <li><strong>Department of Energy (DOE)</strong></li>
        <li><strong>National Science Foundation (NSF)</strong></li>
        <li><strong>NASA</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Department of Agriculture (USDA)</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Department of Transportation (DOT)</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Department of Commerce (DOC)</strong> - NIST, NOAA</li>
        <li><strong>Department of Homeland Security (DHS)</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Department of Education (ED)</strong></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Funding Structure and Award Amounts</h2>
        <h3>Phase I: Proof of Concept</h3>
        <ul>
        <li><strong>Typical Awards</strong>: $75,000 - $750,000</li>
        <li><strong>Duration</strong>: 3-9 months</li>
        <li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Establish technical merit, feasibility, and commercial potential</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase II: Development and Commercialization</h3>
        <ul>
        <li><strong>Typical Awards:</strong> $400,000 - $3,000,000</li>
        <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 12-36 months</li>
        <li><strong>Purpose:</strong> Continue R&D and move toward commercialization</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase III: Commercial Application</h3>

        <h2>Industry Focus Areas</h2>
        <p>SBIR/STTR funding spans virtually every technology sector:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Defense & Security</strong>: Advanced materials, autonomous systems, cybersecurity, sensors, space technologies</li>
            <li><strong>Healthcare & Life Sciences</strong>: Digital health, diagnostics, therapeutics, medical devices, biotechnology</li>
            <li><strong>Energy & Environment</strong>: Renewable energy, storage systems, environmental monitoring, clean technologies</li>
            <li><strong>Information Technology</strong>: AI/ML, quantum computing, advanced computing, telecommunications</li>
            <li><strong>Transportation</strong>: Autonomous vehicles, safety systems, infrastructure, logistics solutions</li>
            <li><strong>Agriculture</strong>: Precision farming, food safety, sustainable agriculture, rural development</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Recent Trends and Opportunities</h2>
        <p>Current SBIR/STTR priorities reflect national strategic interests:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning applications</li>
            <li>Advanced manufacturing and materials</li>
            <li>Climate change and environmental sustainability</li>
            <li>Biotechnology and precision medicine</li>
            <li>Cybersecurity and information assurance</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Key Success Factors</h2>
        <h3>Technical Excellence</h3>
        <p>Your proposal must demonstrate:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Clear understanding of the technical challenge</li>
            <li>Innovative approach with competitive advantages</li>
            <li>Feasible development timeline and milestones</li>
            <li>Strong team with relevant expertise</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Commercial Viability</h3>
        <p>Agencies want to see:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Market analysis and customer identification</li>
            <li>Revenue projections and business model</li>
            <li>Intellectual property strategy</li>
            <li>Pathway to Phase III funding or private investment</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Agency Alignment</h3>
        <p>Successful proposals address:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Specific agency mission requirements</li>
            <li>Published technical priorities and gaps</li>
            <li>Government customer needs and acquisition pathways</li>
        </ul>
